===Etymology 1===
From {{der|en|la-med|lībrāta}}, from {{der|en|la|lībra||pound}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# {{lb|en|now|historical}} A piece of land having a value of one pound per year.

===Etymology 2===
[[File:Libration.gif|thumb|A '''librating''' molecule.]]
From the participle stem of {{der|en|la|lībrāre}}, from {{m|la|lībra||a balance}}.

====Verb====
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|obsolete|transitive}} To place in a balance; to [[weigh]].
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[oscillate]] (like the beam of a balance).
#* '''1796''', {{w|William Cliffton}}, ''The Group'':
#*: Their parts all '''librate''' on too nice a beam.
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To be [[poised]]; to [[balance]] oneself.
#* '''1791''', {{w|Erasmus Darwin}}, ''The Economy of Vegetation'', J. Johnson, p. 138:
#*:Her playful Sea-horse {{...}} His watery way with waving volutes wins, / Or listening '''librates''' on unmoving fins.

